# Serializition

`Serialization` is the process fo converting complex data structures, such as objects and their fields into a "flatter" format that can be sent and received as a sequential stream of bytes. Serializing lets us:
- Write complex data to inter-process memory, a file, or a database
- Send complex data, for example, over a network, between different components of an application
When serializing an object, its attributes are preserved along with their assigned values.

`Deserialization` is the process of restoring the serialized byte stream to a fully functional replica of the original object in the exact state as when it was serialized.

The website's logic can then interact with the deserialized object.

![Pasted image 20230306142928.png](data:image/png;base64,)

Each language serializes in its own way. All of an object's attributes are stored in the serialized data stream, including private fields. To prevent a field from being serialized, it must be explicitly marked as "transient" in the class declaration.

# Insecure deserialization

Occurs when user-controllable data is deserialized by a website. This potentially enables an attacker to mainuplate serialized objects in order to pass harmful data into the application code. Ideally, user input should never be deserialized.

Checking deserialized data doesn't really help, because once its been deserialized it's too late. It's also difficult because a typical site may have a lot of dependencies that it needs taht can potentially be used to inject malicious data. 

# Exploiting insecure deserialization vulnerabilities

## How to Identify Insecure Deserialization

First, look at all data being passed into the website and identify anything that looks like seerialized data. It should be easy to identify if you know the format that different laguages use.

### PHP Serialization Format

PHP uses mostly human-readable string format with letters representing the data types and numbers representing the length of each entry.
`$user->name = "carlos"; $user->isLoggedIn = true;`
Would be represented as:
`O:4:"User":2:{s:4:"name":s:6:"carlos"; s:10:"isLoggedIn":b:1;}`
Interpreted as:
-   `O:4:"User"` - An object with the 4-character class name `"User"`
-   `2` - the object has 2 attributes
-   `s:4:"name"` - The key of the first attribute is the 4-character string `"name"`
-   `s:6:"carlos"` - The value of the first attribute is the 6-character string `"carlos"`
-   `s:10:"isLoggedIn"` - The key of the second attribute is the 10-character string `"isLoggedIn"`
-   `b:1` - The value of the second attribute is the boolean value `true`

The native methods are: `serialize()` and `unserialize()`.

### Java Serialization Format

Jave uses binary serialization formats. They're harder to detect but serialized Java objects always begin with the same bytes, which are encoded as `ac ed` in hexadecimel and `ro0` in base64. If you have source ocde access, take note of any code that uses `readObject()` method, which is used to read an deserialize data from `InputStream`.

## Manipulate Serialized Objects

The basic deserialization exploit is simple. You change an attribute in a serialized object and then pass the malicious object into the website via its deserialization process.

### Modifying object attributes

Say there's a user object that is serialized: `O:4:"User":2:{s:8:"username";s:6:"carlos";s:7:"isAdmin";b:0;}` The attacker will change the boolean for isAdmin to 1, re-encode the object, and overwrite their cookie with this modified value. If the website use this cookie to check whether the current user has access to admin functions then:
```
$user = unserialize($_COOKIE); if ($user->isAdmin === true) { // allow access to admin interface }
```
This code would instantiate a user object based on the data from the cookie, including the modified `isAdmin` attribute.

### Modifying data types

You can also supply unexpected data types. PHP based logic is susceptible to bizarre manipulation because it uses a loose comparison operator. PHP will attempt to convert a string to an integer so 5 == "5 of something" since PHP converts the string to an integer (ignoring everything after the frist part) and then compares the 5 to 5. This logic means that:
0 == "Example String" evaluates to true. There are 0 numerals in the string, so PHP treats it as the entire string is 0.
